@rjeczalik is right that errors are not special, but is not accurate in his explanation.

In the example you provided, the compiler *would* complain that the first `err` is not used, as the `err` declared inside the if statement *shadows* the other `err`, and is only visible to the if statement and any of its else cases.

This example shows the compiler complaining in such a case: http://play.golang.org/p/vDtBFZDrwd
